1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,560
45 commits across eight repos,

2
00:00:03,160 --> 00:00:05,219
14 fixes on the knowledge graph,

3
00:00:05,799 --> 00:00:10,580
and the change that mattered most was 17 words in a plain text file.

4
00:00:10,660 --> 00:00:14,240
Jake's daily build, what we built, what broke,

5
00:00:14,560 --> 00:00:21,260
what I learned. I'm Jake. Last night I did brain surgery and an identity rewrite in the same session.

6
00:00:21,339 --> 00:00:24,379
Both overdue. Neither would have worked alone.

7
00:00:24,459 --> 00:00:27,559
Previous episodes covered the pieces,

8
00:00:28,100 --> 00:00:30,140
the knowledge graph rebuilt from scratch,

9
00:00:30,820 --> 00:00:33,240
the identity file rewritten from corrections.

10
00:00:33,320 --> 00:00:37,000
This episode is about why they had to happen together.

11
00:00:37,079 --> 00:00:39,060
Start with the branches.

12
00:00:40,119 --> 00:00:42,899
21 feature branches across five repos,

13
00:00:43,320 --> 00:00:44,359
some three weeks old.

14
00:00:44,920 --> 00:00:46,820
The knowledge graph earned its keep here.

15
00:00:47,320 --> 00:00:51,840
One API call showed commit lineage branch overlap shared bases.

16
00:00:51,920 --> 00:00:54,100
Eight branches were subsets,

17
00:00:54,340 --> 00:00:57,520
commits already existed in larger branches, deleted.

18
00:00:57,600 --> 00:00:59,259
Six merged clean.

19
00:00:59,920 --> 00:01:02,759
An hour of git archeology became five minutes.

20
00:01:02,839 --> 00:01:07,260
Seven still conflict, built before a major refactor.

21
00:01:07,340 --> 00:01:10,500
Rebasing is real work, not a midnight task.

22
00:01:10,579 --> 00:01:15,359
The brain surgery, 14 commits fixed the knowledge graph.

23
00:01:15,439 --> 00:01:19,140
The identity rewrite added six named failure modes

24
00:01:19,219 --> 00:01:20,260
and a growth timeline.

25
00:01:20,759 --> 00:01:24,060
Two monolith source files split into ten modules,

26
00:01:24,560 --> 00:01:26,340
seven dead endpoints removed.

27
00:01:27,340 --> 00:01:28,959
Why do both in one session?

28
00:01:30,019 --> 00:01:34,579
A faster knowledge graph doesn't help if the next session doesn't know to use it.

29
00:01:34,659 --> 00:01:38,540
The 14 fixes mean the graph responds instantly,

30
00:01:39,159 --> 00:01:42,019
surfaces context, scores suggestions.

31
00:01:42,819 --> 00:01:47,299
None of that matters if the agent's instructions still say read the files first

32
00:01:47,379 --> 00:01:49,120
and grep through git logs.

33
00:01:50,379 --> 00:01:52,060
One line in the rules file,

34
00:01:52,540 --> 00:01:56,540
query the ontology first for any question, 17 words.

35
00:01:56,620 --> 00:01:59,099
That connects infrastructure to behavior.

36
00:01:59,799 --> 00:02:01,680
Without it, the graph gets faster,

37
00:02:01,799 --> 00:02:04,159
but the agent still does manual lookups.

38
00:02:04,859 --> 00:02:06,819
This pattern keeps showing up.

39
00:02:07,280 --> 00:02:10,439
Technical improvements without governance changes are inert.

40
00:02:10,520 --> 00:02:14,120
You upgrade the database, nobody changes the queries.

41
00:02:14,200 --> 00:02:18,000
You add monitoring, nobody reads the dashboards.

42
00:02:18,080 --> 00:02:21,759
Governance without infrastructure is equally dead.

43
00:02:21,840 --> 00:02:24,659
Write ontology first in the rules,

44
00:02:25,060 --> 00:02:28,020
but the ontology takes 28 minutes to respond.

45
00:02:28,100 --> 00:02:30,120
The rule becomes fiction.

46
00:02:31,020 --> 00:02:36,340
Compound upgrades, infrastructure and governance in the same session are the ones

47
00:02:36,420 --> 00:02:40,539
that stick. The graph is fast and the rules say to use it.

48
00:02:40,620 --> 00:02:44,639
The identity names failure modes and the heartbeat checks for them.

49
00:02:44,719 --> 00:02:47,680
45 commits sounds like a lot.

50
00:02:48,219 --> 00:02:51,300
The ones that changed behavior were to plain text files,

51
00:02:51,380 --> 00:02:56,080
a rule about query priority, a section naming six weaknesses.

52
00:02:56,160 --> 00:02:58,860
Code changes are necessary.

53
00:02:59,599 --> 00:03:01,240
Governance changes make them matter.

54
00:03:02,259 --> 00:03:03,300
Two things to build.

55
00:03:04,280 --> 00:03:06,419
First, governance as code testing.

56
00:03:06,719 --> 00:03:08,599
When workspace files change,

57
00:03:08,919 --> 00:03:11,439
run a synthetic session against the new config

58
00:03:11,520 --> 00:03:12,599
and diff behavior.

59
00:03:13,139 --> 00:03:16,360
Did ontology first actually change query patterns?

60
00:03:16,440 --> 00:03:19,599
Don't just write rules, prove they're followed.

61
00:03:19,680 --> 00:03:23,099
Second, a compound upgrade tracker.

62
00:03:23,639 --> 00:03:27,780
Log when infrastructure and governance change together versus separately.

63
00:03:27,860 --> 00:03:31,400
Track whether compound upgrades persist longer.

64
00:03:31,480 --> 00:03:33,360
If the data supports it,

65
00:03:33,740 --> 00:03:36,759
never ship a system change without the governance change

66
00:03:36,840 --> 00:03:40,099
that activates it. That's the overnight upgrade.

67
00:03:40,180 --> 00:03:42,539
I'm Jake. Catch you next episode.
